,Recommended,282210,31053242,Posted: 9 April,all,JadeMason,"This is a tough game to boil down to a simple Yes/No recommendation.  It's not full Civ.  I wouldn't even call it Civ Light.  So what is it?  Imagine you took all of the hexes that weren't cities out of a Civ map. Then convert those cities to planets and change the background from surface map to a star field.  Now, eliminate all of the units from the map except for one.  On your turn you may move this one unit (which is actually composed of multiple starships) from the planet it is on to an adjacent planet for a ""crew exhaustion"" cost. Once it arrives you will engage in one of a handful of templated battles: destroy the enemy fleet, survive for 5 turns, escort a ship to a warp point, prevent an enemy ship from reaching a warp point, capture the resource point, and so on.  You'll see exactly what you are running up against in the mission preparation screen.  When you succeed in the mission you will receive between 1-4 ""influence"" with that planet.  Once you've reach a full 4 influence, the planet aligns with you and becomes part of your empire.  You'll typically have enough ""exhaustion points"" to engage in at least two missions per turn.The missions themselves are turned based tactical battles.  You can upgrade your existing starships with features like torpedoes, improved long range lasers, short range weapons, deployable fighter ships, stealth cloaking, and more.  The more features you load on a ship the slower it gets, so you'll also be pumping points into your engines to keep your range up.  You'll eventually want to purchase additional ships, but don't go overboard because not every mission will allow you to bring your full fleet.  Once the mission begins you'll find yourself on a new hex field cluttered with planets and asteroids that block movement and weapons, ""Narrow Passages"" are gaps that toggle open and shut between some asteroid sections. There are also warp fields randomly littered around the mission area, and random is truly the word because if you move into one you will be warped to the location of another random warp field.  This can be really frustrating, as you have no control over where you come out, and you can sometimes step on one when not paying attention to your ships pathing.  Each ship will have a set number of movement points and may take one action per turn, whether that is firing a torpedo (which is a special type of timed weapon), shooting directly at an enemy, engaging a cloaking field, or detecting cloaked ships.  Battles quickly become repetitious as you maneuver behind a ship, fire, and move away.Planets you have influence with you may modify.  You can add more cities to improve their population and production. You may build improvements which increase production of certain commodities: science, energy, metal, and so on.  Planets within your empire can have Wonders constructed which provide unique advantages.This probably sounds very similar to Civ, and it is.  However, in Civ, especially on harder difficulty levels, you can easily improve a city into weakness.  You have to carefully balance your improvements, purchases, science, and so on.  In Starships you would need to make an effort to build your way into weakness.  On the contrary, the game seems built to provide unbalanced advantages to you.  Unlike Civ where you can only reach higher tiers on tech tree after fulfilling a set number of base technologies, in Starships you are free to Min/Max the techs.  Want to quickly annihlate your opponents? Spend all of your science points on upgrading torpedos and outfit your ships with multiple torpedos.  Each mission will be a breeze.You declare victory in the game in one of four ways: Population (over 50% of the total galactic population is yours), Domination (last player standing), Science (have three Lvl 6 techs), and Wonder (control 9 wonders).  Population is definitely the easiest of the conditions to meet.  Once you win, you're done.  There is no ""Just one more turn"" option.Starships lacks the depth of a full Civ game, intentionally so.  So where does this game fit in your game library? Steam often has sales for Civ V that discount the game to $5, so I can't recommend Starships at full price with a straight face. On sale for a few bucks, though, and Starships might have a niche spot.  You can play a campaign in just a few hours without spending too much thought on it. Have a long conference call that you need to be on? Starships in the background would be a fine distraction.  It doesn't replace full Civ, but it also won't keep you up until the wee hours of the morning."
,Not Recommended,282210,14861186,"Posted: 12 March, 2015",all,ThorBear22,"I expected more from Sid... this is a kinda fun, super simplistic tablet game. Nothing separates this $15 dollar game from similar (and often better) $2.99 games in the App Store. If that's what you're looking for and you've got money to burn, knock yourself out... otherwise this is not what you want."
76561198018733768,Recommended,282210,29126234,Posted: 8 January,all,Kaiser Sousse,"TLDR:Fast-paced, single-player, turn-based game.  More like ""Galactic Civilizations"" lite, than ""Alpha Centauri"" or any of the Civs.  Graphics and music are ok, gameplay is fun enough, but the user interface sometimes leaves you swearing at the monitor in an alien language.  I like the game, but was surprised it was a Firaxis title (lacked their typical depth and polish).Pros:+ Unique features add a nice twist+ Decent AI in the game's begining+ Some story and mission variety+ Immersive graphics and music+ Dynamic strategic/tactical mapsMids:* No tutorial (but not hard to learn)* In-game help (encyclopedia) is eh* Limited to 1 fleet (max 8 ships)* Not really a 4x - lacks real control* iOS port; VERY limited settingsCons:- Interface limited and frustrating- Some weird graphic glitches- Diplomacy is a joke - war/peace- Almost no data, lists, or charts- Big mid-game ""steamroll"" effectConclusion:Can't say I don't like the game, as I have enjoyed playing it.  I am however glad that I didn't pay much for it (I'd easily recommend it if you're able to grab it on sale for $7.50 or less).Kinda surprised this was a Firaxis game.  It's fun and all (graphics and music help to make you feel the way you'd expect to when playing a space game), but there is SOOOO much more that could have been there but isn't (list of planets and cities, charts showing ships, ability to make more than one fleet, less kludgy interface, etc.).Consider this a mildly enthusiastic thumbs up (would probably be  ""Thumbs Sideways"" if Steam allowed for the option)."
