,Not Recommended,282210,14935126,"Posted: 17 March, 2015",all,GnuHorn,"*sigh*  I've played several games at this point and feel that I have a really good handle on the AI in the game.  I *do* find the game enjoyable as a general time-waster, but the game is basically unfinished.  I really, really, really wanted to be able to recommend this game....  I honestly did, but as it stands right now the game is far too buggy, its rules too simplistic, its tactical combat far too imbalanced, and that results in an experience that is frustrating and extremely shallow.I've been playing on easy and, as expected, the AI hasn't really surprised me.  In 10 hours I haven't lost a single battle.  However, I've also lost every single game.  How can this be possible?!?  Well, it's because the victory condition system is horribly broken for the type of game this is (similar to how it's horribly broken in Beyond Earth, only worse).In every single case, I've been defeated by a Wonder victory.""Disable Wonder victories and just allow a Domination victory then!  Problem solved!""Yeah... that's what I've been doing, and it doesn't work.  So I decided to shift my tactics and aggressively go after building wonders... which worked until I got 65% of the galaxy and the rest of the enemies all spontaneously decided to join up together, resulting in a collective Wonder victory.I am literally cleaning the floor with the computer AI and it just declares victory with ... math.And that's possible because at its' heart, all this game is ... is a linear resource race.  Every. Single. Aspect of this game is a linear resource race... and victory would be entirely guaranteed if the Victory system wasn't totally broken.I really wanted to like this game.  I had really high hopes upon reading it and, like I said at the beginning, it's a fantastic time-waster... but the game needs more than bug fixes to solve its' issues.  It needs a rules and mechanics redesign, so I really can't recommend it.I guess at least I don't feel cheated.  I got almost 10 hours out of a $15 game and something should be said for that.  I think the people who worked on this game honestly cared about it, and I think the same is true for Beyond Earth... but ultimately I feel like I just keep dumping money into this franchise because Civ 5 was so darn amazing.  Unfortunately, Firaxis has been basically unable to live up to that triumph with both offerings.I hope that both Beyond Earth and Starships go through an overhaul to fix these massive issues... if that happens, I'll happily return and rewrite this review.Until that happens, I can't recommend Starships.  It's far too broken right now to do so."
