76561198109500046,Not Recommended,282210,22930883,"Posted: 12 May, 2016",all,hobotone,Unstable mess. Forums are full of crash complaints that were never addressed by the devs. No updates in ages.
,Recommended,282210,14873306,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,MaxVector,"I think this best way to sum up this game would be to simply called it ""pocket/mini sized strategy.""Starships comes at a weird time Firaxis and 2K games.  Beyond Earth left many consumers wanting more and genuinely confused.  Why did they charge for a full price game that amounted to nothing more than an expansion pack for Civ 5?   SO what do they do?  They make a game even smaller in scale than BE and charge much less for it.  I assume the strategy now is: ""the price should match the experience"" and what you get with Starships pretty much feels like a $15 game.I'll get this out of the way immediately: this is a mobile game that happens to playable on the PC.  What does that mean?  Well, it means that a lot of the complexity of the Civ series is stripped out and the player is left to make spot decisions and map movement choices.  The interface was clearly designed for tablet touchscreen.  The buttons are in weird places and the menus/screens are stripped to the bar bones essentials.  That said, there is an enjoyable strategy game to be played here.  Let's take a moment to talk about it...The gameplay:Players familiar with Civ 5 will immediately recognize the hex grid format.  The player starts on the grid with a small fleet of starships and a planet.  Each ""turn"" basically boils down to this pattern:- Spend Resources on starships, planets and various upgrades- Move your war fleet to a new planet- Complete the mission on that planet (aka combat, more on this in a moment), thus gaining influence over that planet- MAYBE move again and do a new mission on a different planet- End Turn (aka Shore Leave)Let me touch on the combat scenarios (missions) on each planet:When the players arrives on a new planet that isn't already in their empire, the citizens of the planet will request help in the form of some type of starship mission.  This is where the real strategy of the game comes into play and the theme of ""starships"" really plays out.  Whatever war fleet the player has assembled is now used in a turn based mini strategy game.  It is important to note that SOMETIMES the mission doesn't use the player's war fleet but instead presents some type of puzzle.  But most (>70%) of the time the player must use his/her forces to defeat a squadron of NPC starships.The battle scenarios are most similar to ""war"" in Civ 5.  Each mission is played on its own hex map (separate from the overworld map) where the player manuevers their starships and fires various weapons to destroy the enemy NPCs.    Each starship is its own character on the map so if the player has five starships in their fleet, they now can battle with five ships on the combat map. This is defintely the BEST part of the game.  This is where all the time spent buying new ships and upgrading them pays off.  The player can choose to stay back and use long range weapons to try and get up close and personal with fighters or close range weapons.  If the player is successful, they ""win"" influence over the planet and eventually it folds into their empire.The players wins the entire game when they control most of the overworld map (or lose if they fail to do so).  I *think* its 70%. (Update: There are several victory conditions present but in my play time, so far, I have usually won by accidentally acquiriing 70% of the map.)  When playing on easy mode it is very easy.  Medium and Hard present much better challenges.The truth is that the game isn't very deep.  Upgrading planets and ships usually involves just buying everything.  There aren't really any penalties or drawbacks.  Even if the player concentrates on, for example, energy production, eventually it all evens out.  And that's where Starships is arguably very weak.  This is not a deep game.  The best part of the game is the combat and the starships.  Everything else is nothing much more than a big map the player simply uses to move and drive the game.I found the $15 is worth it.  The strategy of the starship combat is fun albeit not engaging.  The game does retain the ""one more turn"" type gameplay but that's where it ends.  The overall, 4x strategy simply isn't present.Bottom line?This is a $15 strategy game and I recommend it based on the starship combat.  If you want a bigger strategy, with more depth, look somewhere else.Final Score: C"
