,Not Recommended,282210,14856115,"Posted: 12 March, 2015",all,PeteUplink,"From what I've seen of Sid Meiers Starships, I have to wonder why it wasn't just a DLC for Civ Beyond Earth. It's pretty basic.   In fact it feels like it was designed for the Commodore Amiga  30 years ago... If I had played this game 30 years ago I probably would have thought it was brilliant.It's missing many of the things that we take for granted in PC games, like fully adjustable graphics options and the ability to run in full screen.  The mouse controls are clumsy and you can't scroll by moving to the edge of the screen like in other Sid Meier games.At least if it had been a DLC it would have been able to use the in-game display settings of the base game.Sadly I cannot recommend this game. It's the first Sid Meier game that I'v ever been disappointed with...----A quick addition for people who think this game could never have been done as DLC:It wouldn't have been hard to get this to work as a DLC.The game may look different, but it uses the same basic engine (albeit greatly slimmed down). All they've really done is replace the flat terrain maps of Civ with a star field and planets and replaced the normal ground and water based units with space ships. It's basically CIv trying to give the impression of space when it's actually just a 2D hex based RTS like all the other games in the series. Basically the ships aren't flying through space, they're moving along an invisible ground plane, or the equivalent of, with a star background replacing the terrain we normally see. With all that in mind, it wouldn't have been all that difficult to add the maps, units and other features to the main game. There's nothing in Starships that couldn't have been accomplished in the base game.It could have been an add-on for the base game, and added new gameplay features, in the same way that The Sims add-ons often add in new features that weren't built into the base game, but expand upon the original game mechnics."
