,Recommended,282210,19158400,"Posted: 19 November, 2015",all,The Snacrifice,"A neat, small-scale gameSid Meier's Starshipsis a simple, quick, fun little strategy game. Don't go into this game expecting a 40-hour campaign and hours of careful planning, because that's not what this game is made for.Starshipsfeels and plays like a very casual game-in fact, everything from the UI to the simplistic controls and systems screams that this game was built for a tablet or phone rather than a full blown PC. This isn't exactly a bad thing as the UI is clean and easy to navigate, with oversized text and icons.Combat is on a 2d hex grid, with various objects(asteroids, planets, etc.) either blocking vision and fire, or reducing the damage dealt when firing through them. Positioning, shields, and weapon types all factor in as well, giving just enough depth to combat to keep it from getting too stale.There's not really any alien species, just different flavors of humans. All the ships have similar looks and feel, though you can upgrade their weapons and systems in anyway you want, which is neat. I'd have liked more variety but what you get is servicable.You can only have one 'fleet' on the campaign map though, which is a bit annoying.Really my biggest gripe with this game is in the achievements, as you needBeyond Earth(or at least a save game from it) to perfect it.Final Verdict:Decent buy, especially on sale. Scratches that strategy itch without needing 40+ free hours."
