76561197987262228,Recommended,282210,14915006,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,javelin98,"I think a lot of the negative reviews of this game may be due to people expecting a MoO/Civ hybrid, which this game certainly isn't.  However, it is still an excellent game in its own right, much faster moving and with better depth than Sid's Pirates, which is also a game I enjoyed.This game is really quite reminiscent of a tabletop miniatures game combined with an extensive campaign system.  There really are three parts to the game:  resource development, resource allocation, and tactical starship combat.  The first two are accomplished during those times when you grant your crew ""shore leave"" -- a fancier way of pressing the standard Civ turn button -- and watching the enemy players go through their turns.  You have to upgrade planets, develop galactic wonders, repair damaged ships, conduct diplomacy, and research newer and higher levels of technological advancement.  At any point during or after this process, you can send your fleet into combat by attacking another system.This, to me, is the most engaging part of the game.  The tactical combat has a distinctly tabletop feel.  If you've ever played Starmada, Full Thrust, Star Fleet Battles, Battlefleet Gothic, etc., this will be very comfortable territory for you.  The tactical play is straightforward but engaging, with you maneuvering your ships through asteroid fields and around planets trying to both find a clear shot while trying to hide your ships from return fire by using those same obstacles to your advantage.  The maps with asteroids aren't static, either;  the asteroids float about between turns, so you are constantly having to keep an eye on how the tactical situation is changing.  The graphics are absolutely stunning.There are only three weapon types -- a short-range plasma gun, long-range laser, and slow but extremely powerful torpedoes (which can often kill a large ship in one shot).  I find that to be a little disappointing, as I think it would be great fun to design your own weapon systems, as can be done in Starmada.  Still, it gives enough variety to require you to think carefully and plan ahead as to how you will upgrade, employ, and protect your ships based on your resources and intended style of play (charge in, stand off and snipe, torpedo volleys...?).A few other things I wish were different:-- You can only have one fleet.  I'm not sure why this is, as I would far prefer the more realistic model of having fleets assigned to various sectors to reduce reaction times or enable pincer strategies and whatnot.-- It's easy, if you don't stay up on diplomacy and allow the AI players to gang up on you, to become quickly overwhelmed, as your planets are captured faster than you can recover and repair your fleet between combats.-- The diplomacy options could use some fleshing out, and I would love to see some espionage incorporated in the game.Overall, I'd give it a 7.5 out of 10 on my own ludicrously non-scientific grading scale."
