76561197998544057,Recommended,282210,14887661,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,ESSEMKEPLER,"Just finished my first game (on normal), so these are all initial impressions:Much like the Civilization ports for iOS, Starships is linear and short. I actually stumbled into a Wonder Victory while stomping through the galaxy to little resistance -- a domination victory probably wasn't that far off. I'll definitely have to increase the difficulty level in my next try.I didn't find much use for researching tech other than the ambiguous notion that it's helping me somehow. There's little context to tech developments like Artificial Intelligence (what does it mean for fighters to have a 'random module'?). It seems, though, like once I got fighters, the only thing I really needed to focus on was making sure that my starships had too much HP to be taken down.And there's absolutely no use to diplomacy other than to use it as a war on/off switch. You won't find the modifiers that you're used to in the Civ franchise, no helptext around why someone is angry/happy with you other than the general assumption that the closer you are to their border the less likely they are to want to be your friend, and maybe I'm an idiot but I didn't see anywhere where you could trade goods. Also, I found the fact that the other leaders were willing to give up all sorts of information about their empire (like how many ships they have, what their upgrades are, etc.), even in a peace treaty setting, a little weird, especially since war can be ignited as easy as clicking a button (there's no penalty for breaking a peace treaty, near as I've found).Though, I have to say that it's not like I had a bad time. The game seems fun enough for $15. I guess I haven't had a chance to experience the AI at a higher level, so maybe I'll feel like there's more strategic depth to the game once I do that.I mean, it's $15. Obviously not a fully fledged game. It's a time waster, so look at it through that lens before you pull the trigger."
76561197976504053,Recommended,282210,14873739,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Jelikal,"While I recomend Starships, I also give fair warning. This is NOT something you would expect from a Sid Meier's game.I do enjoy playing it, but I also see the short playability of it. Other games from Sid Meier's I can waste many days worth of hours playing. However, after playing this for only a handful of hours, it is already becoming a bit stale.The technical and tutorial issues expressed in other reviews are (as of this writing) are true and in many ways annoying. They do not greatly effect the overall experience though. That is, to me, probably the saddest part of the whole thing. The game is so shallow that even though there are some fairly glaring issues, they do not greatly affect the game. Were they all fixed this instant, it would hardly be noticable in the end. For example, the victory conditions only affecting the player and not the AI. It cuts the game a bit short unexpectedly, but the game play for the most part would be the same.So yes I recomend Starships as it is. The price was reflective of its small stature of a game so it was worth it in my opinion. Try to suspend your disbelief in reguards to its being a Sid Meier's game, or try your best to completely forget it. If you can do either of those thigs you should be fine. Otherwise I suggest seeking professional help from either a psychologist or your local micro brewery.It is at this point I would like to direct my words at Sid Meier and Faraxis ... please, oh please, redo this game in the grand history and style of every other Sid Meier's game made. It has potential and good ideas backing it in story and hope. Please do those things justice and meet the high bar you set for yourselves. Price it as you did Beyond Earth and Civ 5 and if it be as they are in grand stature and bredth, I would happily give my coin in trade."
