76561198030795597,Recommended,282210,14889196,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,kayulves,"First of all: this is not Civilization. If you go into it expecting a full scale space 4X-game, you will probably be disappointed. I see there are a lot of negative reviews complaining about this fact, but honestly, I don't think it is fair to blame Firaxis if you neglected to do your research before buying. Firaxis actually did a pretty good job of showing the game in advance through livestreams which were also posted to Youtube.For what it is, Starships is a pretty good turn based game, with a nice mix of strategy and tactics. It is quite lightweight and simple, but I don't think there's anything wrong with that. The game seems quite polished, and runs really well, as you would expect, as an identical version is available for iPad.And that brings me to my biggest criticism of the game: the PC version seems to actually be *identical* to the iPad version in almost every respect. This means hardly any options menus, and some really annoying interface issues. For example, moving the cursor to the edge of the screen doesn't scroll the map like it would in just about every other modern strategy game. Instead, you have to click the left mouse button and drag the map, just like you would on a touch screen. That's just lazy, in my opinion.Still, I have enjoyed my time with this game so far, and don't really have any problems recommending it. Just be aware that it is a considerably lighter offering than a full 4X. If you are unsure, I recommend that you check out the gameplay videos on Youtube, in which Sid and others at Firaxis also talk about the design of the game."
,Recommended,282210,14895067,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,MiiXD,"I don't know why there is so much hate on this game. It's a small, cut down version of Civ with a combat system. Civ games can take hours to finish and this one doesn't take too long. This game is perfect for people who love the Civ games, but don't want to spend more than an hour on one game."
76561198026733574,Recommended,282210,14872722,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Goragg,"I have to say that I bought this game knowing I was buying a mobile app and not a PC game. My expectations were set for something simple both graphically and in depth.For this reason alone I enjoy the game. It is a simple strategy game I can run through in a couple hours. I did nto expect deep immersion or heavy strategy. The AI is  weak but I have not tried larger maps or more difficult play levels (played on normal).  I do see how this game could be quite nasty between human players! A live opponent won;t let you suck up too many planets and will not fall hopelessly behind technologically. He will also react to any min/maxing you do.Strategic play is simple you get 3-4 'moves' with your fleet. In each move you can attempt to complete a mission to win influence over a neutral planet or attack an opponents. You an build tech, cities, wonders, or buildings on planets. They tend to boost production ot in the case of wonders provide a serious boost to a ship system. The game does not have the wonder race you expect from Civ so no frustrating waste of many turns of resources only to be beat to the unique wonder.Tactically you move around a small map with various debris. There are some advantages to position (back shots hit weaker shields without the smart shield wonder) Lasers are long range and lose less damage though asteroids while plasmas are short range and lose more damage through terrain. Torpedoes are fired on fixed vector and can exploded any time after the first turn. They rarely hit but do force the enemy to move out their way which can allow you to split a larger fleet up. Fighters are an excellent way to extend damage and potentially draw enemy fire from main ships.So in closing if you are looking for Civ5 in space don;t buy this. If you want a fun little strat game to burn some time I recomment it. If you have a few friends you want to trounce I highly recommend it."
76561197972211771,Recommended,282210,14889399,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,Rifter,"I don't write reviews very often, but after reading the negative posts (currently about 50/50 love it/hate it) -- I feel like SID's Starships is becoming a victim of negative ""sheepism"".(There are a ton of well written ""Recommend"" reviews and ""DNR"" reviews out there that cover the mechanics/features of the game.  Go read the top positive and negative reviews if that's what you are looking for, I won't rewrite the same info here.)I will clear up some of the ""top rated"" negative review posts by players who spent ~2 hours in game and therefore believe they have it figured out based on the depth of their experience, and then share negative posts with the rest of the strategy gaming community:- ""All you have to do is capture the enemy homeworld and you instantly have all of their starsystems and resource production.  Rinse/Repeat to an easy victory.""--  Congratulations, you beat the game on Easy Mode (about 10-20 minute gameplay once you figure out a few winning strategies).  However, play the game on Hard/Impossible and you'll find that feature is disabled.  The player must now conquer each system to wipe out an opponent.  Additionally, once you start crushing your current enemy and it looks like you're about to waltz through their empire, the AI is smart enough for that oppenent to *surrender* to another NPC party ts friendly with, thereby converting all of its resources to them rather than allowing you to have them.  Smart.  And a great way to rebalance the game so that the entire game is challenging, not just the first 50 moves.-  ""This this a cheap iOS game port.  Not worth $15""--  Opinions will very on this one.  I agree that the UI and standard PC control (display settings etc) are lacking, but I feel the game works very well on PC in spite of being simulataneously developled for Phablets/Tablets.  I PC game across a triple monitor display, and unlike most recently released titles, the game is solid across any resolution I choose and any window size, while also having multiple other windows/programs open and running.  And its solid.  Not one crash, no glitches, no weird anomolies (granted its not a resource hog).  That's rare.  How many new games out lately suck until version1.5.XX?Besides, dev's are going to follow where the money is.  Think about that when complain about paying $15, the equiv of a fast food meal or a movie on something that you'll arguably get many more hours of enjoyment from.-  ""There is no depth like other SID titles.""--  I'll agree that this game isn't as deep as the CIV series, but it has its place (15 minute to 3 hour long games).  If you are looking for a space based Civ, write the devs, wait a few years, and be prepared to pay $50/60-ish.  But play the game on Large or Epic, and on Hard/Impossible (only after you've played it through a few times on Small/Med -- or you may get crushed), and you'll see some depth.  You'll see how the opening moves are critically important not only in how you design your ships, but where you do the upgrading.  Same for Planet/Star Systems.  BL:  Judge the game for what it is..not because you wanted to Pay $15 for a huge game like Civ-  ""The AI cheats.""--  ...      ....      .............         .................... really? in a strategy computer game? <every AI cheats, harder the level, the more the cheating.>  honestly, I get the frustration at not being able to set victory conditions for both sides (users can only determine/limit their own vic conditions, AI will choose whatever strategy it thinks will help it win).  It'd be a nice feature that might be added by the player comm or devs down the road, but thats more a problem with players not handling their own expectations.  Think outside the box and the feature is just another way of adding difficulty.Final thoughts/Overview:  The game is mostly about it sequential-tactical combat sequences.  This is a direct contrast to the SID Civ titles where global strat/management is the majority and combat isn't developed. There is still a strategic element that if mismanaged will result in a loss, regardless of how good you Tactical execution is.  For the tactical fights, there is something altogether gleeful in a stealthed torpedo exploding in the middle of an enemies battleship formation. Take that you ""17% chance of winning"" estimation!First game -- easy: win. 20 minutesSecond game -- easy: win. 12 minutesThird game -- Moderate: loss. 25 minutesFourth game -- Moderate: N/A. 15 minutes (was losing -- bad initial choices while experimienting. realized how imporant first dozen or so moves are)Fifth game -- Moderate: Win. ~70 minutes6th/7th  game -- Hard: N/A, restarts8th Game -- Hard: Win. ~90 minutes9th Game -- Hard: Win. ~120 minutes (larger maps)10 Game -- Epic: Loss. 70 Minutes11 Game -- Epic: Win.  No idea how long 2-3 hours?12 Game -- Just about to start :-)I've paid more $$ for less game enjoyment out of strategy titles (HoMM and dozens of others).  Its not a perfect game, and does feel *lite* for a PC title, but contrastly would be very *in-depth* for a phone/tablet game (I'd buy it there too).  If the price of a movie is too much for a clever, somewhat deep, interactive space-based strategy game that has potential for re-play-ability, mark it as follow/wishlist and wait a few weeks for it to go on sale.  For my 15-20 hours in game so far, $15 was well worth it."
