,Recommended,282210,14889125,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,Etheras,"Bias warning: I love strategy games, and so I am more inclined to view them positively.Starships is a good game for the price. Its based on an extremely simple mechanic with a few randomly shifting variables that try to introduce some variety (things like: environmental effects, mission types, etc) that can alter the gameplay on a per-mission basis. Its based on the Beyond Earth universe, and will actually read characters out of your Beyond Earth savegames. The whole game is squarely focused around Starships (hence the name), and everything else is built around giving starships modifiers and abilities to make them more effective. Its a turn based game, with the only reflect mecahnic being the ""push button detonation"" ability on the torpedos.The GoodFun, smooth, addictive gameplay (""one more turn!"")Good pure-strategy game (no dice rolls! Whoooo!)2D representation of 3D space much more useful than attempts to cobble together 3D UIs (I've never seen this work in a way that was felt native and intuitive)Extends Beyond Earth for those of us who wanted a bit moreInteresting and new dynamic that we've never seen before (TBS with one ""fleet"", the torpedo mechanic, and others). Could spawn new genresGame length is good for the size of the conceptThe elephant in the room: THE PRICEThe BadGraphics are lackluster. Its clear that this was made being co-developed for mobile.Despite attempts to add variety to the core game mechanic via environmental changes, the game gets very monotonous and repetitive during long gamesThe 2D playfield does feel a bit like a cop-out. While 3D strategy UI has never been intuitive and elegant, maybe they could have tried to make it work, rather than just defaulting to the 2D maps they're so comfortable-with. (makes me think of KHHAAAAAANNNN)While its a good GAME, its only a mediocre VIDEO GAME. It feels a bit like it was designed by tabletop playersNever explained why the leaders of the nations of the world you just conquered would suddenly become the leaders of interstellar empiresVaunted unit customization is limited to ""you have N of a thing""Numerous non-game-breaking bugs. Defeated fleets hang out in the corner of the game map. In diplomacy, leaders still worry about players that have been defeated.No multiplayer (While strategic multiplayer wouldn't have been fun (very long turns), I think tactical multiplayer would have made sense)The enemy AI is pretty easy late-game. It doesn't adapt well to lots of modifiers like Wonders.Game breaking balance issues: Once you have the stealth wonder, you're pretty much invincible at long range. Build that wonder, make lots of laser-heavy fast ships, win.Very symmetric. Aside from initial bonuses and alliances (and ship model) affinities don't seem to matter.In ConclusionGood game, but a very small game without much variety. There's a lot that could be done better. But considering the price-tag, its about what I would expect for that price. No this is not another Civ or Civ-sized game. Plays differently, looks differently, feels different, price is different."
,Recommended,282210,15008000,"Posted: 22 March, 2015",all,Astrolox,"Rather enjoyable little game. It's a very simple turn based 4X in space strategy game, and lots of fun on the first play though. Doesn't really compare to any of the bigger games in this genre though, but that's ok.It gets a little repetitive in late game so maybe wait for a sale before purchasing."
