76561198031704384,Recommended,282210,14896906,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,Ageofchronic,"The game runs well and it looks good graphically. it is really nothing like CIV BE whatsoever, there is a bit of resourse management and research, but all the research is for your ships. Really everything is about your ships, you fly around and do missions for other planets. There are a few different missions you can do, each giving a differnt reward, money, research etc... you have to do a few missions per planet to gain enough influence for them to join your empire. It gets a little old fast doing the missions, depending on what the mission is you may need to outfit your ship(s) diffently. Some missions you only get to use one of your ships, and in others you need to avoid combat more than provoke it. Once a planet has been claimed by an opponent the battles become slightly more interesting and it becomes more about the ship battling and tactics than the missions, which felt like playing minigames. In youre planets you are able to build cities and planet upgrades, the cities boost overall income and the upgrades range in different things like planetary defences and the like. you're crew will allow you to travel a certain distance per turn, limiting how much you can do, without certain upgrades traveling between your cities can eat up you're turns. I did not find much use in the missle weapons, though they seem interesting they are fairly useless, atleast in my experience. The missles travel a certain distance per turn, you may choose to detonate them at any time during their travel but i didnt find the range to be worth it, i rarely used them but when i did i used them to cut the enemy off. The combat zones are riddled with space debris and asteroids, both allowing cover and hindering or dissalowing fire comletely. they are filled with narrow passages between asteroids that open and close (for some reason) between turns. Overall, due to its lower price tag i will recomend it, but it would be best to get it on sale if at all. The game gets old fast but it should be fun to go back to every now and again. I give it a 5/10 and hope that they update it and dont charge for micro-expansions."
76561198009625167,Recommended,282210,14992474,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,yazah,"This isn't a strategy game - or at least not one like Civ, MOO, SINS, etc. It is more like a role-playing game that uses spaceships and turn-based combat.That said, for $10 (its initial release price), it's not bad. I actually quite enjoyed it, it has some replayability, and is worth a few bucks - especially if you can get it on sale. Comparing it to other AAA titles is a bit unfair because it started as a $10 game and isn't much more than that. But it is fun, unique, clever and will give a few hours of gameplay.But it doesn't have the ""one more turn"" additiction of other strategy games.Also, lasers and fighters are overpowered. :) Torpedoes are too, but harder to aim (except against easy AI)."
76561197970599891,Recommended,282210,14879116,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,Roi Danton,"Sid Meier's Starships is a very light 4X game. You control star systems and move a fleet of upgradable ships around while competing with the AI doing the same. There are four victory conditions (wonders, population, domination, science). Once two fleets meet or you attack an enemy planet the game switches to 2D hex-based, turn-based tactical combat.  You can attack enemy ships with lasers, torpedoes, plasma guns and fighters. There is a simple stealth option and there are obstacles on each map that can be used as a cover for ships.On the strategy map you can also upgrade your ships, buy new ships (but you can only have one fleet at a time) upgrade your planets, build cities and wonders and improve your tech level (there are different resources for each task).Now before I start on listing my personal pros and cons I'd like to get this out of the way first: The game is in no way comparable to great 4X games like Master of Orion, Endless Legends and so on. It's a simply game, designed for tablets much like Sid Meier's Ace Patrol. If you want a large, complex 4X-game then don't buy Sid Meier's Starships. Starships is much more of a ""let's play something for 20 minutes"" game than anything else.That said, here are my pros and cons:Pros:- Good Interface- Fast paced combat and strategy map- Fames don't take long to complete (I finished an epic game on normal in 2 hours)- Enjoyable if simple turn based combat- I really, really like the artwork in the game.Cons:- Diplomacy is useless.- The options are a joke (for example: Fullscreen mode only works on my system if I hide the task bar. If the task bar is   not hidden it's always visible and the game doesn't go fullscreen)- The different factions really don't play all that different. And choosing an affinity is mostly about what color you like- The turn based combat is simple. It's really easy to find a strategy that works for you (I enjoy mass torpedo spam for example) and stick with it. Once you have upgraded the first two ships to the max level there is almost nothing that can stop you)Conclusion:I recommend buying the game if you look for something to just play for a couple of minutes and if you enjoy simple turn based combat.I do not recommend buying the game if you look for something complex or challenging."
,Recommended,282210,14907217,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,ODTap,"I liked the whole style of the game. I played a couple full games, and enjoyed them. I love fleets, and how you can upgrade them. Lazer's, armor, shields, fighters, put enegry in to upgrade them. I really liked it, and I would recommend it to Space Fan's. I would like to see multiplayer added in the future, because after a while singleplayer does get boring. Enjoy :)."
,Recommended,282210,14911152,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,PrimusAvatar,"It is, as far as I know, a brand new subgenre of 4X games. Your singular fleet and its advancements are your sole concerns and unlike other 4X games you spend most of your time fighting based on a very fun and surprisingly deep combat system.  The addition of ""wonders"" and battle cards makes a lot of difference on the hexagonal battlefield riddled with environmental obstacles and effects that are a lot more significant than in any other 4x games.However, people hoping to find complexity of a $40+ title are going to be dissapointed. There's been some debate if the game is worth the current price ($15) and my personal subjective oppinion is that a game with this degree of polish despite the lack of $20-$50 content such as ""next gen graphics"", ""unique races"". ""diplomacy"". ""religion"" or ""multiplayer"" is well within it's 10-15$ range. It's a tactical combat game with 4X elements - not the other way around."
76561198030941097,Recommended,282210,14890482,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,mmcgeehan,"This is not Civilization. An  ""epic"" game only takes a few hours (at most) if all victory conditions are enabled.  That being said, it is FUN to play.There is very little strategic management of your ""federation (empire)"". However, small changes have cumlative effects on the outcome of battles. You have the correct combination of effects on the right map and you can defeat a much larger force.  That is actually the best part of the game, the nuances.If you are looking for an epic space 4x game that takes days to complete, look else where.  If you are looking for tactical space battles chained together wtih strategic elements, this is it.Cons :1. The interface is a little flakey, could be improved, but it does function well once you get used to it.2. Game seems shorter than it should (epic really should be epic).Pros ;1. Fast to play2. Easy to learn3. Interesting tactical problems in the battles.Summary - it's only 15 bucks paid waaaaay more for games not half as good or half as fun."
