76561198012014187,Recommended,282210,14897643,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,pieffe8,"After some thought I decided to recommend this game, but with some caveats.The best way I could describe this game is as a simplified version of Master of Orion I, with more emphasis to strategic battles (that cannot be skipped). We have battles, simple planet management, a very simple tech tree. You control only one fleet. You can add ships to it, or upgrade them by increasing the number of weapons, shields, etc...There is no limit on the number of components on the ship, but the cost of additional components increases exponentially.Another difference from MOO I is that you cannot colonize, and every planet is already populated, and by visiting them you can take battle missions, By winning them you gain influence and eventually the planet will become part of the federation. And yes, everything is turn-based.The main focus of the game are the missions. Indeed, you're going to spend very little time managing the planets and more fighting. Battles themself are generally short (about 5 minutes), and you can perform several battles per turn, as you can move your fleet multiple times per turn.Don't try to have long gaming sessions: you'll get bored very soon, because even if there are several types of missions the game mechanism repeats itself over and over again. The game is meant to be played for short periods, like one or two missions at a time. This is fine to me because I'm busy and I have little time playing videogames. No surprise that the game is also for iPad.My main complain about the game is the control system. It doesn't seem really designed for a PC. You can't zoom out in battles or even on the galaxy maps (you can zoom in). Also, it is easy to accidentally move the fleet to a planet you try to interact with. If they fixit my opinion of the game will increase quite a lot.It is good that the game is only $15, but I believe that $10 would probably be a fairer price. So maybe wait for a sale of the game."
,Recommended,282210,14994607,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,CypressMTL,"Firstly, choosing between Recommending this game, and not recommending this game was kind of a hard choice, but in the end I decided to recommend it for what it is.The reason: It's a good game.  It's a short game, but it's a good game.Allow me if you will, to delve into the reasons why I will recommend this; It's a mini-game.  The game itself is made as a companion game but can be played on it's own and is still a bunch of fun.  It's short enough that you can fit in a quick game (an impossibility with other Sid Meier titles), and still leave satisfied.You choose a different ""leader"" which gives you a different boost during the game, but overall I didn't find they made too much of a difference.  Then you really just expand, fight off some ships through an asteroid field, and repeat.  There's a few ""varieties"" of missions, but it's generally just clear out the other fleet, get your ship to a ""warp hole"", or escort a colony ship.  If you're okay with repeating these missions over and over again (with more or less enemies, and a few modifications like reduced visibility) then the game is a fun little time filler.If you're not, then don't buy this game."
