76561198031843846,Recommended,282210,15015080,"Posted: 22 March, 2015",all,Red Earth,"It's all about the starships, so the scope of the same is small and specific. It's fun-size strategy. Like the candy that is either good or bad depending on how much you wanted to begin with.Despite real space being very empty, the battle maps are full of asteroids, and wormholes, and that gives you cover and shortcuts to work with so there's more to think about than just who to shoot.The strategic overworld is important though. In several games I've won every battle but lost the game because an AI won more important battles somewhere else.Equipping ships isn't quite what I'd hoped for. I was hoping for more precision in the choices. Situations where I could determine that one more level of shields would make a world of difference because that would mean a ship would take three hits to defeat instead of two. Doesn't have that. It's more a general: I need more protection-get more protection. It's the strategic layer that more determines how your ships take shape rather than countering something your enemy has.The wonders that enhance your fleet and the modules local planets specialize in give you reason to choose one design over another. If a planet offers cheaper armour that would be a reason to choose to use it rather than shields or stealth for defense. A wonder making your torpedoes undetectable would make them a key weapon in your fleet.The resources your planets provide will determine how you enhance your ships. Excess metal leads to wonders, science to research based bonuses, and energy to bigger fleets with bigger ships. Working with what the game gives you rather than a predetermined plan determines how well you do. This adds to replay in that one game may give you lots of science and cheep fighters but the next offers energy and cannons. You could see this as a loss of choice, if your goal is to find one good strategy and stick with it, but if you'd rather be surprised by and adapt to what you have then this will work for you. We should start calling (tagging?) games like this MacGyver games, because you have to win with not what is the bet tool for the job but, with what you can do with what's at hand.Can't tell yet how balanced the various options are yet, or if having a design theme is necessary or if you can just have all general purpose ships and be fine.I've had fun. It's only $15. Probably better on tablet."
