,Recommended,282210,14857377,"Posted: 12 March, 2015",all,Volcel James Bond,"Let's be upfront about something: This is not a Civilization game, nor does it pretend to be. If you're looking for Alpha Centauri 2 or a rehabilitation of Beyond Earth that isn't a weak Civ5 mod, you're in the wrong place.If you want a board game to play on your computer, then this is exactly what you're looking for.Starships is a compact game probably designed primarily for mobile devices. And you know what? There's nothing wrong with that. Where Starships excels is in its vision and execution of making a game that recreates the board game experience.What's so elegant about Starships is that it takes common board game mechanics and takes advantage of the fact that since the game is being run on a computer, it can develop those mechanics to new heights. Developing planets as your resource generators very much mirrors how a board game might have a chart where you move tokens around to determine how much you get per turn. Special abilities function like cards drawn out of a deck, and the map looks like a game board. Even the victory condition, ""Control 51% of the map"" sounds like something out of a board game.The combat is simple but deep. You get full customization of your units, and you move around on a hex grid shooting at each other with stuff like line of sight, distance, and cover to calculate. It would be unmanageable as a tabletop game (unless everyone playing is a total Warhammer junkie), but as a video game it's very easy to let the computer do all the calculations for you.Like any game worth its weight, the rules are very simple to understand after a turn or two, but there's enough nuance to them that you'll be spending quite a few hours understanding how to optimize everything and adjust on the fly.Major strikes against the game: Missing a lot of basic computer game functions (come on, let me up the resolution!) and no multiplayer. The latter is pretty bad, but then again, it takes a very special group of people to have the patience to sit through a multiplayer 4X game.In short: It's a board game. Don't fool yourself into thinking otherwise. But it is a great board game that takes advantage of not forcing the players to calculate anything on the fly, and blossoms because of that. If you even enjoy the occassional game of Settlers of Catan, this is probably a game you'll enjoy."
76561198086889827,Recommended,282210,14869160,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,LetsGoBuffalo,"Recommended as a standalone, not because of cross-compatability with Civ: BEPlain and simple, this is what I think most people expected of Civ: BE. It's a great standlaone, especially for $15. However, the cross-compatability sucks. You can make a ""new game"" in Starships out of the state of your current Civ: BE game, and get ""rewards"" in Starships for what you've done in Civ: BE. THAT'S IT.Buy it if you thought Civ: BE was ruling the galaxy, not just an exoplanet."
,Recommended,282210,14869403,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Phorth,"Sci-Fi Digital Strategy Board Game( I had to sit down with the game for a number of hours before coming up with the exact reasons why I enjoy it, and it very much earns it's positive recommendation. I'll probably edit this again)It's all about enjoying a digital board game set in space and chilling out. This is a lite-tactical hexagonal space mission game. As captain of a federation, you are charged with bouncing the fleet between planets completing various types of missions and winning over the galaxy that resulted in the wake of Beyond Earth. From the rewards from victories and accumulated resources, you're able to upgrade your ships in a few different ways from increasing their basic health and strength to providing abilities like stealth, torpedo salvos and carrier-borne interceptors. Strategic diplomacy is extremely basic, and amounts to whether you want to deal with the AI directly opposing you or not.The game is very simple, and I recommend watching a ""Let's Play"" on YouTube before buying as it's a large departure from Firaxis' other games. The game feels like it'd be at home on a tablet or phone due to it's simplicity.The gameplay pacing is well suited for short stints for people that want to relax with a small space tactical game. I think it's great to do a full voyage (about 4 missions) and then put the game down for a bit. It's not for great hour long marathons, but a full game might take anywhere from 1-2 hours.So does it reflect Firaxis' Civ ""just one more turn"" philosophy? Probably not. But is that really a bad thing? It depends on what you were looking for. It's great for those times when one is juggling other tasks.There are very few areas where I'd nit-pick it, especially as a single player game. There are many player strategies which are very unbalanced, such as cloaking mixed with some of the Wonders. I would say that the most fun I have is when I pick it up with a particular house-rule for my gameplay that restricts a particular technology or strategy that I'd used prior.I would love to see the ability to mod in and out various aspects, such as to revamp the resources in a drawn out game, and more of the missions reminicent of the exploration phase.From a technical perspective, if this was done in Ruby, I'm impressed and hopeful.I think it'd be a great project for even a scripter or programmer to step in and change things to suit their own tastes."
76561198015971298,Not Recommended,282210,14909563,"Posted: 15 March, 2015",all,Sethkragus,"Even at $14.99 this game is even more garbage then Civ: Beyound Earth. Feels more like a beta/demo then a full game. If you think you are going to have fun customizing ships and planets think again. Planet customizing consist of cliicking a button to add points to resources or population. Ship customization isn't really customization at all, but just add points to like 6 different stats. It's just sad how a great franchise can fall so far but this seems to be happening lately with all big titles. Oh and there is an end game that you can't keep playing after like other Civ games, so onces it's over you have to start a new game :(."
,Recommended,282210,14869215,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,hansilsblood,"Really worth the 15 dollars i spent, when looking at it try not to think of it as its own stand alone game which it actually does really well as, look at it like a future exspantion for Beyond Earth. Because thats basically what it is. Firaxis announced that they are going to tie it in with beyond earth adding another layer of machanics to an already solid game."
,Recommended,282210,14856093,"Posted: 12 March, 2015",all,God-Emperor Quagsire,"TL;DR I wasn't sure I'd like it at first, but then I got into a tactical battle and enjoyed myself. Kind of a mix between Master of Orion and a tactical board game. Not a normal Sid Meier game where you can sink 100s of hours into, takes 1-2 hours to win and worth multiple replays. Not bad for 15 dollars. 8/10===More In Depth Review===Simple Space 4x where you have to get enough of the galaxy fighting for Team Player Character to win the galaxy super election.You start off with one planet, and venture out to other planets to win their allegiance (either through doing quests, buying influence, destroying their factions fleet or simply ending your turn there). On each planet you can make upgrades that will either increase their resource output or add a warp gate (giving you free movement to the planet) or constructing a defensive fleet. Each planet rolls 1-2 random strategic attributes that give it an advantage (such as +50% energy output or 1/2 cost on resource buildings). Each planet also rolls a random tactical attribute such as torpedos being undetectable or more powerful cover from asteroids. A planet also has a chance of having the ability to have a wonder being built on it. All of this is somewhat simple, but there is a real swing factor in gaining or losing a planet with a great combination of attribute that adds a lot of fun to it.Combat is great and where most of the enjoyment is. It's hex based TBS that has a heavy emphasis on cover and positioning.  Ships have three weapons at their disposal- Lasers (long range light damage), Plasma (short range medium damage) and Torpedos (Long Range Massive damage, but very predictable). Ships can also activate stealth (can't be hit with targeted weapons, enemy has to use sensor to find you) activate sensors (for finding stealthed units) or activate impulse drive (trade an action for a single movement in any direction without turning). Effectively, how combat goes is you use asteroids for cover while denying cover to enemies with your torpedoes.Unlike plasma or lasers, torpedoes don't lose damage when fired through an asteroid field. They can't explode the first turn they are fired and continue moving in a straight line for up to three turns. As they automove on the second and third turn you are allowed to make them explode remotely as they move in ""real time"". Being near the center of a torpedo explosion is usually a one shot kill. The explosions also clear asteroids. Torpedos almost never directly get kills against you so long as you move out of their path. The AI doesn't seem to respect them enough though - in the last battle of the game I played I got a triple kill with a torpedo as three ships maneuvered close together to take pot shots at one of my fighters.Your army is a persistent fleet of ships that you purchase upgrades for. Upgrades are pretty predictable (engines give you more moves per turn, lasers do more damage) and there's no real incentive to specialize other then you can't afford all the upgrades at once. There's also a fairly mild experienced mechanic tied to a ship's performance in battle. Science ties into all of this as well, but it's just more simple upgrades to laser damage paid for with a separate currency that effects your whole fleet at once.Wonder balance seems a bit wonky, there are some extremely cheesy wonders like the one that gives you an extra action in combat. It is somewhat limited in that you can't use it on firing lasers or plasma twice in a single turn... but you can fire two torpedos, or release twice as many fighter fleets or attack and then immediately cloak to avoid reprisals.===Overall===+Interesting, Fun Combat+Understandable UI+Powerful feeling planets attributes-Somewhat Questionable AI-Economy and Diplomacy seem simple even by the low standards of economy and diplomacy in Space 4X-A lot of uninteresting upgradesI'd love if it were multiplayer because the combat seems like it'd be more fun if there were living human beings on the other end but for $15 I won't pitch a fit over it. It's an entirely fun single player 4X that doesn't overstay it's welcome and is simple enough for people who don't normally play 4Xs.Sidenote: There's also a lot of mutual unlocks with Civ: Beyond Earth but I haven't explored any of that yet so I'm ignoring it."
