76561198032210434,Recommended,282210,14861264,"Posted: 12 March, 2015",all,eotwdave,"Starships is simply brilliant.  The game is tightly focused on the tactical missions, which is the whole point. The strategic layer is intentionally light to keep most of the playtime in the battles, where it belongs.The missions and ship configurations are varied enough to keep the game interesting through many iterations.Starships is short.  A standard map game can be finished in a few hours, even a huge map game will take a tiny fraction of the time needed to play Civilization. Short is good. I love Civilization, but I can count one hand the number of games of Civ5 I've actually been able to finish in the last two years. And more often than not  Civilization ends with a grinding game of attrition or acumulation of culture points that is simply not that much fun. The strategic game in Starships does a good job of avoiding this kind of slog. The action in Starships builds steadily throughout the game until a satisfying climax in a decisive big fleet battle (at least in my games so far.)There is no multiplayer. This is also a good thing. If you really want a multiplayer online TBS game with both a strategic/political level and a tactical battleboard, then IMHO you really, really have way to much time on your hands and need to get a life.I strongly recommend Starships.I do have two minor quibbles.First, players cannot rename their ships (or I haven't yet figured out how.)Second, the game could use an empire management screen/table to make it easier to find and develop your planets on the larger maps."
