76561198026357688,Recommended,282210,15493004,"Posted: 22 April, 2015",all,DroneCabbage,"This is very much the kind of game which either becomes a cult classic a few years down the line, or simply gets forgotten. It's not really anything like Civilisation at all, there's very little ""city"" (planet) management, and the research gameplay is relaxed to put it mildly. It's really just a turn-based-tactics spaceship battle game with some persistence elements.Those of you who are old enough, I'd like to take you on a brief journey through time. Back to when UFO: Enemy Unknown/XCOM: UFO Defense was new. Remember how the geoscape felt tacked on, like it was providing the minimum amount of glue to get you to the next battle? It's exactly the same here. Replace soldiers and aliens with space ships and, well, other space ships and you'd have something very close to Sid Meier's Starships. That sounds kind of like a compliment, doesn't it? Well, not entirely. The look and feel of the game would really sit quite well in the mid-late 90s (compare Total Annihilation), and frankly the pared-down Civ-like engine for outside of battle is less polished even than XCOM was in its day.In addition to that, and perhaps in some ways as a consequence, the difficulty seems to be miscalibrated. I put it on ""normal"" (from the default ""easy""??) for the first try at playing, and really got straight through to winning the game with pretty trivial ease - maybe 3 battles lost - and that's without ever learning half the interface or discovering where the last faction was. I'd speculate that players who have a reasonable sense of where to put there upgrade points would find it painfully easy on any but the higher difficulties.Thankfully, the actual turn-based battling is pretty enjoyable, and the ship customisation works well. Good for a pick-up-and-play, assuming that you have a couple of hours to spare, and perhaps a worthy antidote to too much Civ."
