76561198100722430,Recommended,282210,14994208,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,Da Bozz,"Nice little strategy game. Its set in space. Theres a load of planets that you can capture and develop (like Civ cities) . There are other races trying to capture those planets before you, and you can ally with them or attack them. Fleet battles are simple, reasonably quick,  hex baseed wargames. Some planets have 'wonders' . And you have a fleet (that you can also upgrade) to fly around exploring and capturing. So far so good. Only issue I have is that you only get one fleet - so its a bit like playing Civ with just one army (and the bigger the map you set the sillier it gets). An update  that allows multiple fleets (plus an option to 'auto fight' fleet battles.) could make this good game great. Certainly doesn't deserve all the bad reviews its getting."
76561198030737080,Not Recommended,282210,14994614,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,Reddy Aimfire,"""Just One More Turn"" no longer applies.  Sadly, my first game ended with me building enough wonders to get a wonder victory, one move away from an absolutely devastating battle between myself (strongest faction) and the second strongest  CPU.  Unfortunately, I'll never get to play that battle because ""Just One More Turn"" is now an extinct part of Sid Meier's repertoire.The game itself is entertaining and enjoyable, if not incredibly dumbed down.  I absolutely love the torpedo mechanic of ship combat, it is something unique and adds a bit of dimension to the otherwise fairly basic combat game play.  However, because of the aforementioned, lack of multiplayer, and other features stripped from the franchise, I cannot whole-heartedly recommend this game.  If it goes on sale for 50% off, it'd be something fun to buy and play for a day or two, but I do not see this game having much long-lasting appeal.  It's more dumbed down that Civ V or Beyond Earth (though the price should be an indicator of that), which I think for some people is a good thing.  However, for people like me, who grew up with Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri, Civ II, the old, ""proper"" Civ games, this just feels like a massive steps backward from already several previous step backwards (Civ V, and Beyond Earth).You decide for yourself if this is the type of game you are looking for.  For me, it's a far cry from the kind of game I could recommend to anyone."
76561197974924722,Not Recommended,282210,15004525,"Posted: 22 March, 2015",all,CPT Chaos,"Bottom-line up front: I'd give this a solid 1.5 out of 10. This is an expensive version of a free Facebook game... read more to find out why.I REALLY wanted to like this game. From the pre-order description, and the fact that Sid Meier does an amazing job with about 95% of the games that they produce, this had a ton of potential.Branded as a 4x game that related to Beyond Earth, I was a bit hopeful to see something that played like Master of Orion 2 and had the space-ground gameplay of Star Commander. Alas, I got my hopes up too high.Also, before you go too much farther with this, just know that I haven't read the other reviews. This is my own take on this game.Everything from the tech, to the resources, (lack of) diplomacy, (generic) space combat, and AI feels flat.TECH: The tech ""tree"" is just a menu of upgrade. There are no new capabilities to introduce and no real choices that force you to examine tradeoffs and benefits. After playing BE, you'll likely be especially let down because NONE of that innovation exists in this game.RESOURCES: Four resources, and four very narrow things to do with them. Like most campy Facebook games, using your resources requires no more thought than a button click.DIPLOMACY: My main complaint with most Civ games is that you have options that the AI will not accept... in this case, you don't even have those options. Your two basic negotiating stances are a) war, or b) peace. Given the combat, neither has any particular advantages.COMBAT: This is probably the only (slightly) redeeming part of this game. For about the first 20 turns, the combat and the missions are challenging. Once you've pumped enough resources into your ships, you can pretty well steamroll the AI with impunity.Oh yes, the ship customization (and the reason why I was excited about this game)... yawn. Again, like the tech tree, the characteristics of each of your ships can be leveled up to attain greater advantage. There is no researching of new ship hulls, engines, weapons, or shields; just leveling. Facebook flash games have more options than this... such as Battle Pirates.Final thing that I'll say on combat is this: one fleet? If SM was trying a new twist on 4x games to limit player to one fleet and up the challenge, this was a terrible choice. Any potential challenge is wasted because they let you construct warp gates so that you do not use up movement points while moving between your own worlds.AI: Now for the AI. Like the rest of the game, the AI is stale and offers no challenge. In three different play throughs of the game (each at increasing difficulty), I have as yet to have an AI player declare war on me or attack me. I can roam the galaxy with my large armada of heavily armed ships and tear through pretty much every other empire with little effort.What could have been a stellar game (see what I did there?) is really just a black hole for your wallet (even at $13 - as of this writing).Save your money. Save your time. Don't save this galaxy (or SM's bottom line)."
