,Not Recommended,282210,21421524,"Posted: 24 February, 2016",all,Kaminobob,"An interesting idea, badly crippled by a lack of (sorry, Sid), Interesting Decision.-There are three weapons to put on your ships (four if you count fighter bays), but one of them is clearly better than any of the others.-You can have a lot of little ships or a couple big ones, but aiming for the middle of the road is clearly better. (you can only fire once per turn, so big ships get outnumbered and surrounded. Hulls have a fairly high cost just to start, so in the part of the game where your money is still limited, it's better spent on improving your existing ships than getting more flimsy money-sinks)-You can upgrade your tech, but all upgrades are flat percent increases of one stat, so the decision is entirely binary. 'Do i have enough science points to upgrade a thing my ships use. If yes, do it."" There's no depth, complexity, or strategy.-There are eight 'leaders', but honestly i would have liked a 'choose random' button because they have no personality (they all speak in a different accent, whoo) and are only differentiated by each having a small, unique advantage.-The AI barely understands how to play its own tactical battles; but if it understood optimal play then an endless slapfight between identical assault cruisers wouldn't be interesting either. I guess I do have to give it credit for making Gallente Style the key to galactic domination, though.-Game modes that aren't conquest continue far past the point where one player (you) is obviously going to win. Game modes that are conquest can be brutally cheesed by sniping homeworlds (which flips their entire empire over to you)Think about it if you ever see it on a tablet app store for $3, otherwise, avoid."
