76561198097842398,Not Recommended,282210,21775977,"Posted: 11 March, 2016",all,The Ever Ruler,The game fails in execution as it suffers from asymmetric difficulty between beginning and end.Now that may sound like virtually every game ever but the goldy locks zone in the middle is short-lived at best and non-existent at worst for this game.  Game starts off with a modicum of difficulty but it's pseudodifficulty in the form of RNG more than actual skill as the AI is dull and repetitive.  This repetitiveness will become apparent once you develop enough resources to escape the mercy of RNG.  The enemy will try the same tactics with the same ships and with the same technology.  The only solace comes in the form of wonders which apply unique upgrades but these do nothing to change the calculus of battle.So basically what starts off as a solid premise with potential ends up being at the mercy of RNG as the game's AI is too dumb to simulate actual difficulty and the balance is too inconsequential to change anything.  This game isn't worth your time let alone your money.
,Recommended,282210,25280577,"Posted: 31 August, 2016",all,Mizstik,"There may be a lot of negative reviews for this game, but for the right people, this game really hits it.If you've ever wanted just the turn-based tactical combat without the baggage of empire management, this is the game to get. If you've ever set up a Civ5 game on a huge epic pangaea with only elimination victory type, you might want to try Starships using epic + impossible + domination-only setup. You get the fun battles with much less empire management baggage and with much less possibility for lopsided technological mismatch.And if you want turn-based combat in the form of starships in space, this may well be the only modern take in existence because I haven't managed to find any other. Most other 4X games have gone real-time with combat and they come with massive empire management and ship design overhead.Here are a sample of things I liked compared to other tactical (mostly RPG) games:- You can reconfigure your party instantly with little to no resource loss, promoting build diversity. You can refit your fleet into any spec to suit the next battle and respec it back. In most other tactics game, you're locked into particular builds accompanied by long grinding process which you have to repeat if you switch builds.- The game gets going fast with minimal build-up time. Within 2-3 battles, you're already progressing up to considerable strategic options (e.g. cannons, fighters, new ship). In most other tactics games, you'd have to grind around for dozens of missions to gather resources and gain EXP.- The galactic screen is essentially a very good mission chooser screen. Most other tactics games offer very little choice with regard to choosing missions. (e.g. limited to open sidequests, random battles that interrupt your travel, etc.) In Starships, you can look at your borders and choose a mission based on the other empire's strength and your crew fatigue. Mission types on non-federated planets are quite varied.- Planetary Wonders are a really nice way to differentiate the strengths of each player in the game in a way that's halfway between randomized and controlled, and also in a way that you can't plan for from before the game starts the way you could with Civ5 leader traits or world wonders.- No random chance to miss. (looking at you XCOM) Cover reduces damage instead of chance to hit.The only real complaint I have for this game is the lack of multiplayer, although ultimately its addition would probably be no more than what multiplayer was in XCOM which didn't really do much.Another possible complaint is that the AI is not terribly difficult, but I find that it only really has problems when you start using special tactics (like invisible torpedoes). In an open brawl, I find that the AI is quite competent with finding odd line of sight that I can't fire back to and are pretty good at finding a way to shoot your engines. The Impossible difficulty should be good for the vast majority of average players.I like what the game has to offer in its current (and probably final) state and wholeheartedly recommend it for fans of turn-based tactical space games."
76561198023917415,Recommended,282210,25184664,"Posted: 27 August, 2016",all,Canadian Sniper,"I love this game. I have been waiting for something like this for a very long time. Their could obviously be improvments such as adding multiplayer, or having the ability to design how your ships looks, but overall this game is amazing. The one thing that this game fails at, is its pricing. It is way over priced! But, if it goes on sale, I would highly recommend this game, especially if you have ""Beyond Earth"""
,Recommended,282210,25875582,"Posted: 5 October, 2016",all,Reliant39,"This is a great, streamlined strategy game with a heavy focus on -- surprise, surprise -- building a fleet of starships and improving their stats. You improve the ships by spending resources and you get the resources by exerting ""influence"" over planets (basically, you conquer them). You can buy influence or gain influence by either completing a mission at the planet or by giving your crew shore leave there. Shore leave basically serves as an ""end turn"" button on the main strategy map and allows your crew to rest and recover, so you can move again next turn from planet to planet, improving them (by building cities, improvements, or wonders) and gaining influence.Aside from the main strategy map, you'll also be conducting an awful lot of combat missions on a more detailed battle map. You'll fire torpedoes, which you can detonate at will after the first turn when an enemy is nearby (or you think it's nearby), or perform scans, or simply shoot an enemy vessel with your ships' weapons. Asteroids little the 2D battle arena that provide some cover for your vessels as you manoeuvre into an advantageous position. The best thing? These battles, while numerous, move very quickly, so you'll never get bored.You can win the game through a variety of means, though the most common one is the ""population"" victory, where you control 51% of the galaxy. The end isn't particularly exciting: you'll get a dialogue box that essentially tells you, ""You win!"", followed by a short and rather nondescript video. But the game is fun! Yes, it's nowhere near as complex and involved like any of the Civilization games, but it isn't supposed to be. This is Sid Meier's Starships, not Sid Meier's Galactic Empires. It's streamlined and simple without being simplistic. You'll be doing all the standard 4X things: exploring, expanding, exploiting, and exterminating, but at such a brisk pace you can easily finish a full game in a couple of hours or less.If you expect this to be the next big Sid Meier game that will devour your life for months if not years on end, you'll be disappointed. (And incidentally, congratulations on having so much spare time on hand!) If instead you're looking for a quick, fun turn-based strategy game with lots of fairly interesting options and brisk combat, then Sid Meier's Starships is worth your time and money. I thoroughly recommend this."
,Recommended,282210,25785257,"Posted: 30 September, 2016",all,Lane,"There's a good and grand idea behind this... and I enjoy this game quite a bit. But it's missing the bulk of what you'd expect from a space strategy- and there's a lot out right now.A good mobile game, a bit lacking for a sit down PC game. Still worth a try."
